channel.title: Frontenac Racquet Club
channel.description: The sweet spot for St. Louis tennis.

wp:termmeta.wp:meta_value:
In the summer, FRC pros are all over town.

Love to play on clay? Mark McPhillips has a full schedule of activities planned at The Highlands in Forest Park.

If hard courts are more your thing, spend your summer at Shaw Park in Clayton, with Carolyn.

Of course, Terry's at Old Warson, Stefan's at Westwood and Jennifer's at Greenbriar – as always.

So pick your program, pick your pros, pick your place. But the important thing is, pick up your racquet and get your game on!

item.title: Pros
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
Meet our pros! They make our club the sweet spot for developing your game.

The FRC pro staff is second to none. Manager Terry Ward has been with the club since 1982. His leadership and drive make FRC the dominant indoor tennis club in the St. Louis area. Second-in-command Stefan Kruger has been with us since 1998. He adds the structure to bring you and your family a consistently first-rate experience. Together they lead one of the most dynamic groups of young pros anywhere. Offering everything from private lessons to group classes, these young pros deliver the finest instruction in the country.

The Frontenac way.

At FRC we follow the traditional path: simple preparation, simple follow-through. No swinging volleys. No modern forehands. Tried-and-true has served us well since 1975. We continue to emphasize the fundamentals that make a great tennis game. Plus, you'll always get a warm smile and a welcome hand. It's the Frontenac way.

item.title: Karim Madatali
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded: The director of our Top Guns program, Karim is a P1 USPTA Certified teaching pro who's been at Frontenac since 2002. He runs Monday Night Singles and men's interclub. In the summers, he's been the Director of Tennis at the Westborough Country Club since 2005.Originally from Vancouver, Canada, Karim earned several national top-30 singles rankings as a junior - and a Junior World Ranking in doubles.At Maryville University, he played #1 Singles and Doubles and earned First Team All-Conference honors from the St. Louis Intercollegiate Athletic Conference in 1999. In 2006, the St. Louis District Tennis Association named Karim Adult Player of the Year after he finished 2005 as the #1 Singles Player in the St. Louis Area. That year, Karim and former FRC pro Kevin Lackey were the Association's #1 Doubles Team.He has also coached college tennis since 2000. As Maryville's head men's coach from 2000-2008, his players earned both All-District and Academic All-American Honors. Now he's the head coach at Fontbonne.Karim and his wife, Erica, have two girls.

item.title: Kyle O'Leary
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
A graduate of Duquesne university, Kyle played three years of college tennis there, with 69 career wins and two years as team captain. He spent his freshman year at the University of Hartford, playing both soccer and tennis.

Junior tennis.

As a junior, Kyle ranked as high as 130 in the U.S. and as high as #5 in the Missouri Valley – and competed at the Kalamazoo (Hard Court) and Clay Court Super Nationals. At Lindbergh High, he was a four-time District champ in singles and, in doubles, teamed up with FRC's Kyle Tosie to reach the state finals.

Summers and other seasons.

In the summer, Kyle teaches at Bellerive Country Club in Ladue. In spring and fall, he's the Washington University men's assistant tennis coach. Kyle holds a degree in business and sports marketing. Around the club, he runs Ladies' Play with the Pros and works with the Top Guns kids. You can reach him here by email or at (314) 369-1153 by text.

item.title: Maria Steinbach
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded: One of the top women players our area has produced and a member of the St. Louis Tennis Hall of Fame, Maria has been at Frontenac since 1980. As a junior, she ranked as high as seventh in the world, reaching the finals of both the Junior French Open and the Junior U.S. Open. She also played at Wimbledon. At Brigham Young University in Utah, Maria was All-American in 1978 and 1979. Maria and her husband, Tyler, are the parents of three.

item.title: Peter Hantack
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
A Division Two college coach at several schools over the years, Peter is the head coach at Maryville University.

Playing days.

A St. Louis native, Peter played his college tennis at UMSL – also a D2 school – and still holds the all-time record for most singles wins in a career there. He was also ranked in the top 80 in Norway.

What's up with Peter now?

Peter works with the Top Guns juniors, the drill groups and the junior instructional clinics.

item.title: Rusty Jones
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded: Rusty joined FRC in November 2011, when he and his family moved to Town & Country from the Tehachapi Mountains of south central California. Ironically, Rusty played college golf after struggling to choose between his two favorite sports. But after he won a USTA singles tennis event in Calabasas, California, the hosting club's tennis director invited Rusty to teach professionally. He never looked back. Since 1988, Rusty has taught at prestigious country clubs across California, rising to the level of head pro at the home club of a young rising star named Sam Querry. As a member of the California PRINCE Sports Advisory Staff, Rusty competed at Indian Wells in Prince's private events with ATP tour pros Juan Carlos Ferrerro, David Ferrer, Xavier Malisse and Guillermo Coria. Certified P1 with the USPTA, Rusty holds a business degree and did his undergraduate work in English/Communications at California State University Northridge. He also wrote the book META Tennis: A Handbook for Folks not Necessarily Wimbledon Bound. Rusty and his wife have two teenage daughters in school at The Principia. Click below to meet: Terry Ward - Stefan Kruger - Rusty Jones - Peter Hantack - Mark McPhillips - Maria Steinbach - Kyle Tosie - Kyle O'Leary - Karim Madatali - Jennifer Wilhelm-Zeuschel - Clark Taylor - Chris Nasrallah - Carolyn Kramer - Jordan Snyder

item.title: Jordan Snyder
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
Jordan joined the staff here in the fall of 2012 and runs the Wednesday women's drill group. He's also heavily involved with the juniors' Top Guns program.

Playing career.

After making his Florida high school's district finals in both singles and doubles, Jordan moved to St. Louis in time to play for Pattonville as a senior. And what a move that was! His 21-3 match record that year included conference and district championships and a trip to the state tournament. In college, Jordan played #5 and #6 singles and #3 doubles at SIU, where he majored in sports administration.

item.title: The FRC summer camp for juniors.
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
Chris Ward, a tennis instructor at Frontenac, will supervise this year's tennis camp – indoors at the club.

Download a brochure and claim your children's spaces now!

Joining him will be Clark Taylor, also a member of the FRC staff. A certified USPTA professional, Clark has been instrumental in establishing Quick Start programs across the St. Louis area and is a USTA tournament director. The camp is designed to work on the vital skills young players need to become solid high-school players:
  • Proper grip.
  • Early stroke preparation.
  • Proper swing patterns.
  • Ball control.

New for 2014. The FRC training center!

This summer, we'll also have 45-minute Tiny Tots classes for children ages 3-6. For details, please contact Clark Taylor at 304.654.5925 or by email here.

Things to know.

Location.

Camp is at Frontenac Racquet Club, 10455 German Boulevard.

Schedule.

Ages:

Contact:

Call Jana Erb at 314-963-3061. Don’t call the club.

Facilities:

The club has bathrooms, water and a telephone.

Bring:

A small snack and plenty to drink. Teens and advanced players should bring two racquets.

Group & Private:

Lessons are available via Chris Ward at 314.346.3210 or chrisw@frontenactennis.com and Clark Taylor at 304.654.5925 or clark@frc-tennis.com.

item.title: David Conley
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
If David was a little late getting back to St. Louis for the opening of our 2014-15 season, he had a pretty good excuse: He was a line judge at the US Open. A member of the Saint Louis Association of Tennis Officials since 2006, a credentialed line umpire/sectional chair umpire for the USTA and more recently a line and chair umpire for the International Tennis Federation, David officiates at tournaments all over the country.

Mostly, though, David loves teaching.

A full-time pro at Frontenac during the year, he's spent his summers at high-profile tennis programs from John Newcombe's Tennis Ranch in Texas to Meadowbrook Country Club here at home. Starting in 2013, he has been the director of tennis at Warson Woods – and still taught with Mark McPhillips at the Highlands in Forest Park. David holds an MBA from Missouri Baptist University and has worked in customer-facing roles for the Cardinals, the Rams and the Chaifetz Arena. You can email him here or text him at (314) 707-3523.

item.title: Meet Pam Busch –
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
Every little kid’s best friend.

 

Did you know that Frontenac is one of only two clubs in the area that offer child care while you're on the court?

Back in the day, every club offered care. But apparently, that's no longer true. At Frontenac, though, your kids will find a room all their own with soft, squishy sofas to relax and snuggle on; a colorful mural that fills a whole wall with fun characters and storage of every type that's stocked from floor to ceiling with toys, toys, toys! Presiding over this children's paradise: the comforting presence of Pam Busch, a seasoned child-care expert with grown children of her own. Since her arrival for the 2009 season, Pam's become a much-loved member of the FRC team. Her daughter, Kelly, works part-time at FRC as well.

item.title: Ladies' clinics and practices
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
Ever wonder what goes on at a Ladies' Interclub practice?

Several regulars at our ladies' Interclub practices say they're the highlight of their week.These fast-paced tennis clinics follow a specific format:
  • a 20-minute warmup, often with cardio intent;
  • Two drills that cover a specific theme, generally developed over several weeks;
  • A game of doubles points that integrate specific skills from the theme (named craps, after the casino game);
  • A cooldown of real doubles or a combination of doubles and the game known variously as Queen of the Court, Three and Take Over or Rush 'n Crush.

The Frontenac difference.

At other clinics you may have taken, there's a pro or two circulating among four or five tennis courts – giving advice as the players set up the drills for themselves. At Frontenac, there's a pro on every court, feeding in balls and making sure the drills teach the concepts as planned. They're also there to answer questions as they come up, about strokes, strategy and more. So in a 90-minute practice, more time gets spent on the theme of the day and less on chasing errant balls.

Take a look!

Here are several weeks' worth of demos and drills boiled down to just under eight minutes of video from our 1 pm practice on Tuesdays. Thanks to pros Mark McPhillips, Carolyn Kramer and Clark Taylor; players Nancy Hinkson, Lisa Hilton and the rest of the Tuesday gang.

item.title: Wow! It's Mats Wilander, here in St. Louis!
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
Mats and his business partner, Cameron Lickle, will play an exhibition match against Terry and Stefan on Saturday afternoon, right after the Doubles Classic final. Want to know more about their WOW program? Here's a pdf brochure you can download.

About Mats.

A former No. 1 player from Sweden, he won seven Grand Slam singles titles from 1982 through 1988:
  • Three at the French Open.
  • Three at the Australian Open.
  • One at the US Open.
He also won a Wimbledon doubles title in that same period.

A winner on every surface.

In 1988, he won three of the four Grand Slam singles events - everything but Wimbledon - and wound up the year ranked No. 1. And while Mats never did win Wimbledon in singles, he did win the Australian Open when that tournament was still played on grass. That makes him one of just five men to win Grand Slam singles titles on all three surfaces: grass, clay and hard courts. The other four are Jimmy Connors, Andre Agassi, Rafael Nadal and Roger Federer. And he and Nadal are the only two men ever to have won at least two Grand Slam singles titles on all three surfaces. What's more, when Mats won his fourth Grand Slam title, he was just 20 years old - the youngest man in history to reach that milestone.

Mats in the Davis Cup.

In the Davis Cup for Sweden, Wilander's record is 36-16 in singles and 7-2 in doubles. But his most memorable Davis Cup match came in defeat, in what is still the longest match in Cup history. And it happened right here in St. Louis, on carpet, against John McEnroe, in 1982. The final score: 9-7, 6-2, 15-17, 3-6, 8-6. the match lasted a grueling six hours and 32 minutes.

Don't miss Mats and Cameron on Saturday, May 18.

Tickets are just $10/person or $15 for your whole family!

The tennis event of the year.

A one-night event for its first four years, it has attracted a who's-who of St. Louis tennis. Beyond top area pros on the court, observers include longtime industry insiders, friends and family – and tennis fans from a 50-mile radius. The event seats more than 800 spectators at the Frontenac Racquet Club.

From one night to a weekend of tennis action.

2013 is the fifth annual competition – and will see the event grow to span two days, as one of two marquee events of the 2013 St. Louis Tennis Hall of Fame Festival. The Festival also features Mats Wilander's WOW program and an exhibition match. Early rounds will start at 6:30 pm Friday, May 17 and end with the final at noon Saturday, May 18.

Previous winners.

Classic champions in years past have been: 2009: Jalal Chafai and Dani Adalberti. 2010: Terry Ward and Ken Nordheim. 2011: Kevin Lackey and Billy Gluck. 2012: Wynn Criswell and Dave Reinhart.

Two more Hall of Fame inductees: Jane Pratt and Jack Eggmann.

Jane Pratt.

Rick Randall told the crowd about how Jane ran all the tournaments at Dwight Davis with a loving but firm hand - and a sharp eye on the books. And that was while maintaining a championship-level doubles game of her own, with her longtime partner, who was there to accept the award on Jane's behalf.. The Top Guns Competition program is for any player who would like to compete in local and regional tournaments, play high-school tennis and perhaps college tennis.

Small groups
8-10 students per class
Positive reinforcement
No yelling or screaming.
Good strokes, good grips
Basics are top priority.
Good fun
  • Mon/Tues focus on singles.
  • Wed/ Thurs focus on doubles.
Hard work
Players who don't focus on improving will be asked to leave the program. Download a brochure: choose printable or iPad format.

item.title: Tennis Lore
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
Journalist/Hall-of-Famer Ron Cobb has your local tennis history right here!

It’s all in his new book – only at String ’n Swing.

Former St. Louis Post-Dispatch tennis writer Ron Cobb has collected his favorite tennis stories in a new book, St. Louis Tennis Memories. Taking a step beyond his original reporting at the time, the book also updates us on a number of the people featured in the articles, showing us where they are now. Himself a recent inductee into the St. Louis Tennis Hall of Fame, Ron tracked down former St. Louis champions from Florida to California – and Australia – for his updates, which include Jim Parker, Bob McKinley, Leo Estopare, Jennifer Prah, Juan Farrow, Bruce Foxworth, Todd Hammonds, Blair and Mary Ellen Strassner, Toby Clark, Chris Gillis, Siri Eklund, Mauricio Sovero, Laura Guignon and dozens more. The book also features an index of more than 850 names of St. Louis people mentioned in the stories. If you played tournaments in the ’80s or ’90s, your name might be there! String 'n Swing is also the new home of the St. Louis Tennis Hall of Fame, which was previously housed at the Triple A Club, and showcases a display of more than 500 vintage tennis ball cans from the private collection of Bill Tao, who acquired them over several decades in his travels around the world. You can find the book only at String 'n Swing Tennis (314-995-6860), a shop that opened in March in Old Frontenac Square. That's on the northwest corner of Lindbergh and German Blvds., next door to The Shack.
